    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="2"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.1012 Anti-War/68</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 207</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-13">March 13,
                            1934</date>.<lb/>[Received March 22.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s telegram No.
                    28 of February 20, 1934, I have the honor to enclose a printed copy of the
                    Anti-War Treaty of Non-Aggression and Conciliation which, it will be noted, has
                    been certified as a true copy on page eleven thereof.<note n="2" xml:id="d2fn2"
                        >The certified text is that contained in República Argentina, Ministerio de
                        Relaciones Exteriores y Culto, <hi rend="italic">Tratado Antibélico de
                            no-agresion y de conciliacion</hi> (Buenos Aires, 1933), pp. 3–11. Copy
                        of this booklet is filed under 710.1012 Anti-War/68. For English translation
                        of text, see <ref target="frus1933v04#pg_234">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 234</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In this connection I have the honor to enclose a copy of the Embassy’s note No.
                    78 of February 26, 1934,<note n="3" xml:id="d2fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    requesting the copy of the treaty and informing the Argentine Government that it
                    is the Department’s understanding that the treaty is no longer open to signature
                    and that non-signatory states may become parties only by adherence.</p>
                <p>There are also enclosed a copy and a translation of Foreign Office note dated
                    March 12, 1934,<note n="3" xml:id="d2fn4">Not printed.</note> which was received
                    today, transmitting the certified copy of the treaty and confirming the
                    Department’s understanding.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Alexander W. Weddell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
